<has-cmf>The provided Facebook ad data does not contain a CMF number.  This is not conclusive evidence of non-violation, as it's possible a CMF number exists but isn't included in this dataset. However, its absence is a point in favor of the ad not being electoral propaganda.</has-cmf>
<refers-to-candidate>The post's body contains only unintelligible characters.  Therefore, it does not specifically refer to any parliamentary candidate.  Article 36 (7) - a does not apply.</refers-to-candidate>
<addresses-the-wide-population>The ad is a paid Facebook post, targeting a wide audience based on the provided demographic data (age, gender, location).  It addresses the wide population. </addresses-the-wide-population>
<electoral-objective>Given the unintelligible nature of the post's text, it's impossible to determine if it has an electoral objective. The lack of discernible content prevents a determination of whether Article 36 (7) - c applies.  In dubio pro reo, we must assume it does not have an electoral objective.</electoral-objective>
<journalism>The unintelligible text prevents assessment of whether the post is journalistic in nature.  It cannot be determined if it aims to educate or inform.</journalism>
<personal_opinion>The unintelligible text prevents assessment of whether the post expresses a personal opinion. </personal_opinion>
</analysis>

<conclusion>
<post_id>873046971577096</post_id>
<electoral-propaganda-analysis>
The Facebook post contains unintelligible characters in its body.  This makes it impossible to determine if it constitutes electoral propaganda.  The absence of a CMF number and the lack of any identifiable reference to a candidate or party lean towards a conclusion that it is not electoral propaganda. However, the paid nature of the post and its targeting of a wide audience are factors that could suggest otherwise if the content were decipherable.  Given the uncertainty due to the unintelligible text, the principle of "in dubio pro reo" should be applied.
</electoral-propaganda-analysis>
<electoral-propaganda-decision>FALSE</electoral-propaganda-decision>
